'''''Encyclopedia of the Central Intelligence Agency''''' is a 2003 book by [[W. Thomas Smith, Jr.]] It is an [[encyclopedic]] work on the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA), the only [[Independent agencies of the United States government|independent agency]] of the [[federal government of the United States|United States federal government]] that is tasked with [[United States Intelligence Community|intelligence-gathering]]. The work chronicles the history of the agency from its founding in 1947 through the [[War on Terror]]. It provides approximately 550 entries in 282 pages on topics including individuals, intelligence operations, historical events, and depictions of the CIA in fictional media.

The encyclopedia was praised by ''[[School Library Journal]]'' for its reference value and comprehensiveness. ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' was critical of the author's objectivity and lamented that he wrote with a positive bias about the agency's intelligence operations, but concluded that the book was still a useful reference tool.

==Background==
''Encyclopedia of the Central Intelligence Agency'' is authored by [[W. Thomas Smith, Jr.]]<ref name="in100" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Check it out - What's new at the Lexington Public Library|work=[[Lexington Herald-Leader]]|location=Kentucky|date= February 22, 2004 |page=E7}}</ref> Prior to authoring the work, he served in the [[United States Marine Corps]] as a [[paratrooper]] and leader within the infantry.<ref name="sabalos" /> Smith worked as a journalist for the ''Star-Reporter'' newspaper, and subsequently taught students [[journalism]] at the [[University of South Carolina]].<ref name="sabalos" /> 

The author was interviewed by the [[Columbia, South Carolina]] newspaper ''[[The State (newspaper)|The State]]'' about his book and his interest in researching the history of the [[Central Intelligence Agency]].<ref name="sabalos">{{cite news|work=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]]|location=[[Columbia, South Carolina]]|title=5 questions with W. Thomas Smith Jr., Author of a book on the CIA|date=July 25, 2003|first=Sarah|last=Sabalos|page=E5; Section: Weekend}}</ref> He explained that he had held an interest in researching [[military history]] for a significant period of time, and was initially asked by the [[American Society of Journalists and Authors]] to put together a monograph on the 1944 [[Invasion of Normandy]] by [[Western Allies|Western Allied]] forces during [[Operation Overlord]] in [[World War II]].<ref name="sabalos" /> His literary representative later telephoned him to ask if he would be interested in instead writing an encyclopedia detailing the history of the CIA.<ref name="sabalos" /> Smith felt this was an attractive task due to the relevance of the CIA to military history.<ref name="sabalos" />

==Publication history==
''Encyclopedia of the Central Intelligence Agency'' was first published in 2003 by [[Facts on File]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Online Computer Library Center|year=2014|work=[[WorldCat]]|accessdate=March 5, 2014|title=Encyclopedia of the Central Intelligence Agency|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/encyclopedia-of-the-central-intelligence-agency/oclc/451060528|publisher={{oclc|451060528}}}}</ref> It was released in both hardcover,<ref>{{cite book|first=W. Thomas|last=Smith, Jr.|authorlink=W. Thomas Smith, Jr.|title=The Encyclopedia of the Central Intelligence Agency|publisher=[[Facts on File]]|year=2003|isbn=978-0816046669|series=Facts on File Library of American History}}</ref> and paperback formats.<ref>{{cite book|first=W. Thomas|last=Smith, Jr.|authorlink=W. Thomas Smith, Jr.|title=The Encyclopedia of the CIA|publisher=Checkmark Books|year=2003|isbn=978-0816046676}}</ref> An [[eBook]] edition was published the same year.<ref>{{cite news|author=Online Computer Library Center|year=2014|work=[[WorldCat]]|accessdate=March 5, 2014|title=Encyclopedia of the Central Intelligence Agency|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/encyclopedia-of-the-central-intelligence-agency/oclc/536324166|publisher={{oclc|536324166}}}}</ref> Additionally an eBook was also published in 2003 in Great Britain.<ref>{{cite news|author=Online Computer Library Center|year=2014|work=[[WorldCat]]|accessdate=March 5, 2014|title=Encyclopedia of the Central Intelligence Agency|url=http://www.worldcat.org/title/encyclopedia-of-the-central-intelligence-agency/oclc/860296064|publisher={{oclc|860296064}}}}</ref>

==Contents summary==
Within ''Encyclopedia of the Central Intelligence Agency'' author [[W. Thomas Smith, Jr.]] discusses and defines key concepts integral to intelligence gathering, including "clandestine mentality", a colloquial term used to characterize a syndrome wherein spy officials become consumed with paranoia.<ref name="in100">{{cite news|title=In 100 words or less|work=[[New York Post]]|location=New York, NY|date=July 27, 2003|page=57; Section: Arts and Entertainment, New York Pulse|publisher= N.Y.P. Holdings, Inc.}}</ref> The book is 282 pages in length.<ref name="sabalos" /> The encyclopedia contains approximately 550 entries on intelligence topics, including roles of individual members of the agency, key historical events, major intelligence operations, and depictions of the organization in fictional media.<ref name="school" />

Starting with the foundation of the agency in 1947, the author provides the reader with a chronological overview of CIA history.<ref name="publishers" /> He documents the extent of the CIA's involvement in the [[1953 Iranian coup d'<U+00E9>tat]].<ref name="publishers" /> Smith provides a biographical assessment of the motivations of [[Mohammad Mosaddegh]], leader of Iran prior to the coup.<ref name="publishers" /> Smith gives brief entry descriptions of individuals, organizations and events related to the history of the CIA, including Russian intelligence official Colonel [[Vilyam Genrikhovich Fisher|Rudolf Ivanovich Abel]] and U.S. intelligence operation utilizing front company [[Zenith Technical Enterprises]].<ref name="sabalos" /> The chronological presentation of CIA history grounds the reader in background of the agency's involvement with the [[War on Terror]].<ref name="publishers" /><ref name="school" />

==Reception==
In a review by ''[[School Library Journal]]'', Smith's encyclopedia was praised for its reference value.<ref name="school">{{cite journal|journal=[[School Library Journal]]|title=Encyclopedia of the Central Intelligence Agency|first=Dana |last=McDougald|year=2003|publisher=Reed Business Information, a division of Reed Elsevier Inc.}}</ref> The review called the encyclopedia comprehensive, and noted it contained helpful appendices including a glossary, lists of executive staff members of the CIA, and a large bibliography and index.<ref name="school" /> ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' reviewed the encyclopedia and criticized Smith's objectivity, writing that he wrote positively of the operational successes of the agency throughout its history.<Ref name="publishers">{{cite journal|journal=[[Publishers Weekly]]|title=Book review: Encyclopedia of the Central Intelligence Agency|year=2003|publisher=Reed Business Information, Inc. }}</ref> The review concluded that though the book had problems with neutrality, it was still a useful reference work for key terms and events related to intelligence.<ref name="publishers" />

